We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the:
i) BAC Chairman and BAC Secretariat, in coordination with the City Budget Officer, to submit the City’s approved APP and Supplemental APP to the GPPB and COA; and strictly observe the regulations prescribed by the revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
ii) BAC Chairman and BAC Secretariat to invite Auditors and other observers, in writing, in all stages of procurement process including the bid evaluation and post-qualification proceedings;
iii) BAC Secretariat and concerned departments to submit an advance copy of contract and supporting documents to the Audit Team; and
iv) BAC and BAC Secretariat to submit explanation/justification on deficiency noted on the advance bidding process conducted for the Fabrication of Concrete Barriers; and
v) TWG, BAC Secretariat, and concerned departments to submit the lacking documentary requirements to the Audit Team and/or provide justification if the lacking document/s is/are not applicable to the project.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct concerned Officials to:
i) formulate in-house guidelines/programs for each type of assistance and consider the following inputs, among others:
a. qualifications of beneficiaries for each program;
b. standard amount to be allocated for each program to avoid excessive disbursement and unequal distribution of assistance to beneficiaries;
c. documentary requirements to avail of the programs; and
d. limitations on the frequency beneficiaries can access the programs.
ii) ensure that assistance is correctly charged against the designated program;
iii) conform to Sections 48.2 and 48.3 of the RIRR of R.A. No. 9184 for the procurement of casket;
iv) ensure that list of beneficiaries/payroll with its supporting documents are duly attached to DVs or liquidation report;
v) stop the practice of utilizing financial assistance funds to cover expenses for conventions, seminars, and other similar activities;
vi) ensure the inclusion of all types of assistance in the AIP; and
vii) ensure that each assistance is properly planned to avoid non-implementation.
Lastly, we recommended and Management agreed to:
i) carefully assess the application of each beneficiary to avoid granting financial assistance to individuals who are not legitimate residents of the City; and
ii) submit proof that the four individuals who were granted assistance under Angel Health Care are bona fide residents of the City.

We commended CGT's efforts to alleviate the burdens faced by its constituents. However, the identified deficiencies indicate inadequate management of programs due to the absence of official guidelines. This absence resulted in an unequal distribution of funds among intended beneficiaries. Implementing policy and guidelines can establish eligibility criteria, determine the amount of assistance for each type, and outline the necessary supporting documents.
Furthermore, the Management informed the Audit Team that the drafting of in-house guidelines for CGT's various programs is underway. The Chief of Staff of the Mayor's Office has directed the CSWD Office to undertake this task, with the intention of submitting the guidelines to the SP for appropriate resolutions.
