Management commented during Exit Conference that they will adhere to the recommendations of the Audit Team.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:

Provincial Social Welfare Development Officer (PSWDO) furnish the Accounting Office with copy of the distribution list for welfare goods and prepare the SAR thereon;

Acting Provincial Accountant

determine the composition of the accounts Non-Accountable Forms and Other Supplies Inventory, verify whether the items composing these accounts still exist, and make the necessary adjusting entries in the GF and JEV, if needed; 



adjust the balances of account Other Payables account in the TF books by recognizing the inventory accounts in recording procurement made in CY 2016 and prior years; and

 make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the errors in recording of supplies and materials consumption; 



concerned Supply Officers of district hospitals  prepare and submit promptly their monthly supply consumption report to the Accounting Office; and



Acting Provincial General Services Officer and IC devote time to conduct the periodic physical count of inventory and render reports thereon.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:

Acting Provincial Accountant and the Acting Provincial General Services Officer exert efforts to:

(i) investigate the causes of the unreconciled difference and make the necessary adjustments; 




(ii) coordinate and record all donated PPE items during the year including unrecorded PPE items from previous years, if there are any;




(iii) prepare and maintain the required records and reports of all PPE accounts; and 



(iv) determine the cost or fair market value of fixed assets held out for rent or capital appreciation to facilitate their reclassification from PPE to Investment Property;


the Acting Provincial Accountant instruct the responsible employee to compute depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation for all depreciable assets; and 

Acting PGSO together with the IC, complete the conduct of physical count covering all classes of properties owned and/or in the possession of the Province when the circumstances permit.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:

Local Finance Committee (LFC), the Provincial Governor and members of the Sangguniang Panlalawigan (SP) continue to appropriate an amount equivalent to at least five percent of estimated revenue from regular sources in compliance with the requirement of RA No. 10121; 

Acting Provincial Accountant instruct the concerned accounting staff to transfer the unspent current year’s LDRRMF to special TF account under the account title Trust Liability-DRRM; 



IC and Acting Provincial Accountant  determine the actual Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies consumed, make the necessary adjusting entries and properly account for the unused supplies; and 



concerned officials of the Province submit the lacking documentary requirements to the Audit Team so that transactions may undergo further evaluation.

We recommended and the Provincial Governor as Chairman of the Provincial Local School Board agreed to:


ensure the full utilization of the fund for projects/services to intended beneficiaries; 




see to it that the funds are equitably distributed in the budget preparation to address the budgetary needs for the operation and maintenance of public schools; 






direct the concerned DepEd School Division Superintendent to submit the required distribution list of the uniforms/supplies for validation of the Audit Team; and 



Acting Provincial Treasurer intensify collection of RPT shares from the municipalities in order to increase collections and consequently increase the SEF share to fund its PPAs.

We recommended and the Provincial Governor agreed to: 

require the Human Resource Management Officer to attach the lacking documentary requirements to the DVs pertaining to hazard pay to prove the regularity and propriety of the claims and submit the same to the Audit Team; 



direct the Acting Provincial Accountant to see to it that all necessary supporting documents are attached to the DVs, including duly signed/accomplished documents before processing the claims; 





demand the return/refund by the payees of the hazard pay granted on March 16, 2020 amounting to ₱30,000.00; and



require the Human Resource Management Officer to attach the lacking documentary requirements to the DVs pertaining to the SRA to prove the regularity and propriety of the claims and submit the same to the Audit Team.

We recommended that the LCE:                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               

instruct the CGS Officer and the Chief, CEEMO to strengthen its monitoring capabilities over the lease contracts and improve its strategy to properly implement the regulations in the market place; to enforce faithful compliance of the stallholders to the stipulations in the contracts and to impose appropriate and timely penalties against the erring stallholders;

direct the Chief, CEEMO and Treasury to demand the immediate payment from the obligors who breached the stipulated schedule of settlement of their liability under the compromise agreement; repossess the occupation and the control of the stall space, if warranted and in coordination with the City Legal Office, institute legal measures to recover the aging receivables;

require the responsible officer/s to recover or locate the contract of lease mentioned above and furnish copies to the Office of the Auditor to enable the appropriate examination of the related transactions; 

through coordination of the CGS Officer, make representation to the Sanggunian Panglungsod to draft and enact a legislation fixing the rental charges for City’s market spaces which are not yet covered or governed by any law or ordinance; and

instruct the City Legal Officer to study the lease contracts and institute appropriate legal measures, if there is any, to immediately address the widening disparity between the rental fees earned under the existing contracts and the standard rates, at the very least, as decreed by the existing City Market Code.

We recommended that the MO and CAO:

Consider the provision of storeroom for palay seeds and fertilizer or if not feasible, plan the procurement properly so that distribution could be done in the shortest possible time after delivery;  

Review the criteria on the selection of beneficiaries considering the GAD issues to be addressed  and the expected output/outcome of the program in attaining the objectives;

Establish more detailed guidelines of the program to include documentation and maintenance of records with respect to distribution, proper collection and remittance of beneficiaries’ equity and periodic preparation of monitoring report; and

Observe properly the timing of procurement such that distribution could be performed ahead of the planting season.

We further recommended that the BAC and its Secretariat ensure that all procurement documents contain complete and consistent information and submit explanation/justification/documents for the issues noted in the post audit, including the minutes of pre-bid conference clarifying the details of the subject item of the procurement process.

