We reiterated the recommendations on which the LCE agreed to:

constitute an Inventory Team which shall conduct a complete inventory taking of PPEs and Inventories and prepare the required RPCPPE;

instruct the CGSO (i) maintain the required property records including AREs; (ii) ensure the proper management of motor vehicles by avoiding  the imposition of inappropriate markings/displays on any unit thereof and dispatching or transferring without proper documentation; (iii) cause the immediate registration or renewal of City owned vehicles at the LTO and make sure that all vehicles shall bear government plates; 

instruct the Accounting Office to (i) update its records on PPE accounts and reconcile them with those of the CGSO; (ii) continue to exert effort in retrieving prior year’s information in order to bring the accounts and the supporting ledgers into agreement; (iii) compute and recognize depreciation expense for all the depreciable assets of the CGT; 

require the concerted efforts of City Architect, Accounting, Treasurer, Planning and Development Officer, and CGS Officer to recover the documents such as the list of qualified beneficiaries/claimants in resettlement areas, contracts or memorandum relevant to possession or occupation of their respective premises, and establish  the amount of credits or receivables that has to be recorded       in the    City’s 
books    as    of    date;     and

instruct the Legal Officer to review  the contracts and institute  appropriate  measures to demand and collect receivables from delinquent claimants-debtors or initiate legal action, if warranted.

We reiterated the audit recommendations that the LCE:

Instruct the City Agriculturist to revisit the agreement on Livestock Dispersal and recommend the amendment of the same to settle the deficiencies noted in the audit; demand the recipients to comply with their obligations on return of offspring and repayments of loans; conduct periodic monitoring of the Program, and  prepare and maintain reports thereon for decision making purposes; 

Direct the CAO to submit dispersal documents and status report relevant to the Program to the Accounting Office;

Require the Accounting Office to review the dispersal documents and properly adjust the overstatement of Inventory account; and

Enjoin the City Veterinarian and City Agriculturist to take appropriate action on the disposition of animals in the hands of the supplier costing ₱1,093,850.00 in order to avoid the possible loss and wastage of government resources.

We recommended that the LCE 

instruct the TCDRRMO to coordinate with concerned offices to comply with COA Circular No. 2014-002 and obtain donation documents in order to recognize properly the donated properties;

through the CHRMO, consider and facilitate the hiring of regular TCDRRMO staff who shall perform the delegated functions prescribed by the existing rules and regulations;

comply with the minimum standards on early warning and communication, responders kit and medical health, additional power and hand tools;

direct the TCDRRMO to submit the list of recipients for the distribution of the relief goods for CY 2017;

require the TCDRRMO, CSWDO and CGSO to institute appropriate measures and cure the gaps in managing, accounting, recording and reporting the transactions for relief goods;

instruct the Accounting Office to recognize inventories as of December 31, 2017;

instruct the TCDRRMO to properly prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with Annex A of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and

require the BAC and its Secretariat and other concerned offices to submit explanation/justification/documents for the issues stated in paragraph 7.8.

We recommended that City Mayor instruct the:

BAC Secretariat to submit (i) APP and the corresponding PPMPs; and (ii) the lacking documents noted in audit;

requestor in the PR, BAC and Technical Working Group to (i) submit explanation/justification for non-compliance of the procurements on the PNDF and DPRI requirements; and (ii) ensure compliance with the DPRI, PNDF, R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 in all subsequent procurements of drugs and medicines;

GSO and the Pharmacist to (i) submit explanation on the discrepancies of quantities per count and per procurement documents; (ii) transfer the stocks of medicines to appropriate property room/stockroom to maintain products’ integrity observe; and (iii) observe the proper inventory maintenance by regularly monitoring and preparing appropriate reports respecting inventories;

GSO and CHO, with her collaboration, to properly plan the procurement of drugs and medicines in consideration of availability of stock all throughout the year and submit explanation why the Angel Cut Project was implemented earlier than the delivery of the needed medicines and  supplies; 

OSCA to submit certifications from its members proving the receipt of medicines distributed to them; and

City Accountant to (i) properly record in the books, under perpetual system, the procurement, receipt and disposal/consumption of inventory items based on the reports submitted and duly certified by the GSO and the Pharmacy; and (ii) recognize the necessary adjustments to correct the misstated inventory accounts at year-end.

We further recommended that the City Mayor in coordination with:

CHO and Pharmacy evaluate further the Libreng Botika operation vis-à-vis patients’ conditions i.e. consumption of time and cost for travel; 

GSO ensure that proper stockrooms can be used before the procurement in bulk of stockable drugs and medicines; 

SP consider to revise the guidelines/procedures governing Libreng Botika particularly on the process of distributing/dispensing of drugs and medicines taking into consideration the clear requirements for presentment by the beneficiaries; and

HRMO consider to include the appropriate duties and responsibilities of the Pharmacist as provided by pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the contract or appointment of the City Pharmacist.

We recommended that the LCE formulate/conceptualize and install an effective mechanism pertaining to fund transfers to barangays by:

directing the responsible offices to consider only those barangays’ requests which articulate a particular program, project, or activity proven to be a necessity in the community;

delegating to able officers the functions of monitoring the barangays’ PPAs funded by subsidy and conducting assessment and evaluation thereof for decision making purposes;

entering into agreements or contracts designed to promote accountability and to ensure the proper management or utilization of government funds; and

instructing the City Accountant to properly recognize the financial assistance as Due from Other LGUs, require the recipient barangays to submit liquidation reports; and review whether the funds were disbursed for the specified purpose.

We recommended that the LCE 

Comply with Section 12 of R.A. No. 9003 with respect to constitution of TCSWMB;

Include in the SWM program the optimal utilization of electrically operated shredder and bailer extractor to avoid disparagement due to idleness;

Continue the good practice on the operation of MRF at Barangay Tibag;

Settle the issues on the Joint Venture Agreement entered by the CGT;

Consider the adoption of a decentralized solid waste management system by providing financial and technical assistance for the establishment and operation of functional and standard-based MRFs in all the 76 barangays or clusters of the barangays of the CGT; 

Coordinate with Barangay Officials to educate their respective constituents in the implementation of R.A. No. 9003 specifically the mandatory segregation of wastes;

Direct the CENRO to comply with the requirements of R.A. No. 9003 on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and continue to exert efforts in collecting wastes that are properly segregated;

Strictly monitor the requirements provided for by the contract of service between Metrowaste Solidwaste Management Corporation  and CGT particularly on wearing of uniform and personal protective paraphernalia and if violated, imposed such penalties indicated therein;

Consider the review and amendment of the CGT’s Anti-littering ordinance specifically the amount of fines to be paid by the apprehended violators; and

Consider increasing the workforce of CENRO for more effective implementation of the Anti-littering ordinance.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the CSWDO, BAC and other concerned offices to 

henceforth, conform with the implementing procedures and scheme provided by DSWD and SIA in the execution of the supplemental feeding program to ensure full attainment of the program’s objective;

adhere strictly to the rules and regulation of RA 9184, faithfully comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002and cease the practice of making cash payment on the procurement of goods that should undergo competitive bidding;

stop the practice of paying for undelivered goods in strict compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations; and

submit the lacking documents stated above.

