We recommended that the LCE -
through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;
through the CENRO, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and direct the garbage collectors to collect only those garbage that are properly segregated;
expedite the review of the Joint Venture Agreement entered into with MRF-ITECH to determine with finality the best location for the operation of MRF activity of the agency, and take appropriate action to speed up the repair of electrical wirings of the CGT MRF in Brgy. Tibag so it could maximize the utilization of the equipments therein;
consider adopting a decentralized solid waste management system by providing financial and technical assistance for the establishment and operation of functional and standard-based MRFs in all the 76 barangays or clusters of the barangays of the CGT;
continue the apprehension of violators of the anti-littering campaign of the CGT; and
instruct the Solid Waste Management Board to convene for the revisions of the Solid Waste Management Plan and submit to Environmental Management Bureau for approval.
The LCE together with the City Legal Officer and the Executive Assistant of the Vice-Mayor explained that they have already talked with the Management of the MRF-ITECH and are planning to rescind the contract because the equipment provided can only process 30 tons of waste per day while the City’s waste daily is 120 to 150 tons.
The Legal Officer and the City Administrator also explained that the MRF-ITECH was not able to present an Environmental Compliance Certificate.
The LCE further enumerated her plans, to wit:
Visit barangay schools to encourage waste segregation;
To test, and if warranted, to adopt the technology of an Engineer in the CGT who created a shredder; and
To distribute said shredder to the barangays.

We recommended that the LCE:
Instruct concerned officers and employees indicated in the issued Notices of Suspension to immediately institute available remedial measures to justify the cost deficiencies detailed above;
Instruct the Engineering Office to a.) cautiously inspect projects vis-a-vis approved programs of work before accepting the same; and b.) to label supporting pictures as to “before” “during” and “after” and indicate the date when the pictures were taken;
instruct concerned offices to submit the above stated necessary documents for the evaluation of the project Construction of City Health Center II in Barangay Matatalaib, Tarlac City; and
instruct the Accounting Office to examine carefully, with the assistance of the Engineering Office, the completeness and correctness of supporting documents for infrastructure projects.
The Management agreed to implement the audit recommendations.

We recommended that:

(a)	the Local Finance Committee (LFC) continue to appropriate 20 percent of the agency’s annual IRA to development projects in compliance with the mandate of the LGC and DILG/DBM JMC No. 2011-1;

(b)	the SP continue to appropriate funds for the general welfare of the agency and its constituents, taking into consideration the criteria of necessity and legality of the projects and programs sought to be implemented;

(c)	the CPDO strive to improve the performance of the agency in terms of project delivery by endeavouring for the implementation and completion of projects and programs pipelined during the budget year; 

(d)	the City Engineering Office (CEO) require the project contractors to observe the format and design of project signboards as prescribed by the COA; and

(e)	the City Mayor or his authorized representative inform the COA ATL about the project signboards installed/posted as required in the COA Circular for verification purposes.

We recommended that:

(a)	the City Mayor continue to strengthen partnership with national government agencies for the implementation of priority projects beneficial to the people of Tarlac City;

(b)	the CAO submit the liquidation reports for the cash advances granted to CSWDO as well as the disbursement vouchers supporting the unaudited expenses of the CHO;

(c)	the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and its Secretariat submit the lacking documents pertaining to the (i) farm to market road implemented in Barangay San Francisco, Batang-Batang and Villa Bacolor and (ii) procurement of drugs and medicines using PHIC funds;

(d)	the CSWDO (i) continue to implement the Supplemental Feeding Program in accordance with the stipulations in the Memorandum of Agreement with the DSWD; (ii) furnish COA copy of the Post-Implementation Report or equivalent report/evidence to prove that the reported NNC and feeding activities were indeed accomplished; (iii) attach similar report to future NNC and Supplemental Feeding Program liquidation reports to be submitted to COA for the Auditor’s verification; (iv) follow up with the CGSO and CAO the liquidation documents for the unsettled cash advances used in the feeding program; and 

(e)	the CMDESO (i) consider seeking clearance from the COMELEC for the distribution of the negokarts to the beneficiaries inasmuch as these had been procured long before the election period began; and (ii) take serious steps to address the complaints raised by some beneficiaries of the livelihood starter kits.

We recommended that:

(a)	the City Mayor require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer, or their representatives, to reconcile their records pertaining to the account Due to BIR, particularly the remittances made to the BIR and to make necessary adjustments, if necessary;

(b)	the City Accountant (i) submit the remaining paid disbursement vouchers for CY 2015; and (ii) request from the City Mayor the replacement of accounting personnel who continuously fail to render reports on time so as not to compromise the over-all performance of the City Accounting Office.
